{
  "query": "To attract natural enemies for pest control, what is the comparative evidence for using manufactured chemicals versus planting non-crop plants that produce attractive chemicals?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from conservation biocontrol research, there is substantial data on both manufactured chemicals and non-crop plants for attracting natural enemies, though direct comparative studies are limited. For manufactured chemicals (Action 754), 5 of 13 studies found more natural enemies, with effects varying between enemy groups, sites, or study dates. Eight studies found positive effects varied between conditions, and 4 studies found more natural enemies with some but not all test chemicals. In terms of pest control outcomes, 3 of 9 studies found fewer pests using manufactured chemicals.\n\nFor non-crop plants producing attractive chemicals (Action 724), evidence from four studies (China, Germany, India, Kenya) showed more consistent results: three studies found higher numbers of natural enemies in plots with attractive plants, and all four studies found decreased pest populations or damage. One study also found increased crop yield.\n\nPlanting flowers as pest regulation (Action 1400) showed 3 studies found greater pest reduction or higher parasitism rates, and 2 studies found more natural enemies in fields with planted flower strips, though effects were sometimes inconsistent.\n\nThe evidence suggests that non-crop plants producing attractive chemicals show more consistent positive effects across studies for both attracting natural enemies and reducing pest populations, while manufactured chemicals show more variable results that depend on specific chemicals, environmental conditions, and target species.",
